# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: b-clark-burchfiel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf was a member of the National Academy of Sciences and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He served as president of the Geological Society of America in 1944 and received its Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] His second wife, Eleanora Knopf, was a notable geologist and frequent collaborator.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf was born December 2, 1882, in San Francisco, California, to German American immigrants.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He grew up with his family on a ranch near Woodside, California.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf entered the University of California, Berkeley, where he became a student of petrology under Andrew Lawson.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He earned a Bachelor of Science degree in mining geology in 1904 and a Master of Science degree in 1905.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] That same year he spent the first of six summers surveying the mineral deposits of Alaska for the United States Geological Survey (USGS).
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] In 1906 he moved to Washington, D.C., to work for the USGS full-time.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] The Alaskan Division, of which Knopf was one of about a dozen members, was considered the best geologic group in the USGS at that time.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf's work on tin deposits in the Seward Peninsula became the basis of the dissertation for his Ph.D., which he received from Berkeley in 1909.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] In Alaska he also discovered the minerals hulsite and paigeite.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] In 1911 Knopf was promoted from assistant geologist to geologist.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Over the next nine years he undertook a series of field projects for the USGS, beginning with the mining district in Montana that includes the Boulder Batholith and continuing to other western states including Nevada and California.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] In the latter state he surveyed the Gold Country.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] After discovering that universities on the eastern seaboard were paying about double the USGS salaries, Knopf left the USGS for a teaching position, and a number of his colleagues followed suit.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale University in January 1920.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He encouraged students to work with the USGS as he had done; this helped mitigate the agency's brain drain following the departures.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf began at Yale as an associate professor but was promoted to full professor in 1923.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He was named the Silliman Professor of Geology in 1937 and a Sterling Professor in 1938.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He was director of graduate studies from 1933 until his retirement from Yale in 1951.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Upon retiring he returned to his native Woodside, California, settling not far from his family's old ranch.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] There he accepted a visiting appointment at the Stanford University School of Earth Sciences, where he remained until his death in 1966.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf's field work continued through his Yale and Stanford appointments, again with a focus on western states.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He continued his work in the Boulder Batholith and investigated intrusive igneous rock bodies in the Spanish Peaks in Colorado.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He also contributed to the emerging field of geochronology, putting lower bounds of 2 billion years and later 4.5 billion years on the age of the Earth.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1931.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He was also a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences and of the Geological Society of America.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1944, and he received the Penrose Medal in 1959.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] In 1937 he was vice president of the Society of Economic Geologists.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] In 1908 Knopf married Agnes Burchard Dillon.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] They had three daughters and one son, though one of the daughters died in infancy.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Agnes died in 1918 in that year's flu pandemic.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] In June 1920, Knopf married fellow USGS geologist Eleanora Frances Bliss, who as Eleanora Knopf became a frequent collaborator and travel companion.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] When Adolph moved to Yale, which did not then hire women, Eleanora worked out of Adolph's office, teaching private classes and still accepting USGS assignments.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] When they moved to California, Stanford hired her as a research associate.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Knopf died November 23, 1966, in Palo Alto, California.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] In his will he endowed a chaired professorship at Yale.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] The sitting Adolph Knopf Professor of Petrology is Shun-ichiro Karato.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Adolph and Eleanora Knopf also endowed a graduate fellowship in petrology at Stanford.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/adolph-knopf] Mount Adolph Knopf in Juneau Borough, Alaska is named after him.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/albert-w-bally] Bally started his career at Shell Oil Company, retiring as Chief Geologist after 27 years in 1981.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/albert-w-bally] After retirement, he joined Rice University as chair of the Department of Geology and Geophysics.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/albert-w-bally] He remained active in the department until his death in 2019.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/albert-w-bally] In 1988, Bally was elected President of the Geological Society of America.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] Winchell graduated from the Wesleyan University of Middletown, Connecticut, in 1847.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] He then taught at Pennington Male Seminary of New Jersey, Amenia Seminary of New York (where he had previously been a student), an academy in Newbern, Alabama, and the Mesopotamia Female Seminary of Eutaw, the last of which was founded by him.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] He became president of the Masonic University at Selma, Alabama, in 1853.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] He was elected as a member of the American Philosophical Society in 1865.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In 1854 Winchell entered the service of the University of Michigan as professor of physics and civil engineering.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] Eventually he became professor of geology and paleontology at Michigan.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In 1859, Winchell was appointed as State Geologist of Michigan for the newly formed second geological survey of the state.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] He held the post until 1863 when the state did not appropriate funding to continue the survey.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] The survey was resumed in 1869, and Winchell was reappointed in April.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] Owing to conflicting opinions between Winchell and his superiors, he resigned in 1871.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In 1863 Winchell took up a lease on a cotton plantation near Vicksburg, Mississippi, under a plan devised by Gen.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] Lorenzo Thomas to lease plantations along the Mississippi River to loyal men from the North, who would hire black laborers on terms prescribed by the army.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] Winchell organized the Ann Arbor Cotton Company and sold stock to the university's president, whereupon he received a leave of absence to engage in cotton planting.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] General Thomas set wages at a low level ($7 per month for men, $5 for women, minus the cost of medical attention and clothing).
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] Even then, many lessees defrauded the freedmen of their earnings.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In the winter of 1863–64, the Treasury Department briefly assumed control of the Mississippi Valley labor system, mandated a substantial increase in black wages, and contemplated leasing the plantations directly to the freedmen.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] The venture brought him only problems, and after he returned to Michigan in 1864, his brother Martin, who was managing the plantation, was killed by guerrillas.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In 1872, he was appointed chancellor of Syracuse University.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] The depression of 1873 affected both his personal finances and those of Syracuse, and these troubles led him to resign this position in 1874.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In 1875, he worked as a professor of geology and zoology at Vanderbilt University.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] There, his views on evolution, as expressed in his book *Adamites and Preadamites: or, A Popular Discussion* (1878), were not acceptable to the University administration because they diverged from Biblical teaching.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] Today the views on the "inferiority of the Negro" (quote from his 1878 book) would probably have been the focus of controversy.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In any case, he was obligated to resign in 1878.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In 1888, he co-founded the Geological Society of America in Ithaca, New York along with John J.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] He served as the 3rd president of GSA in 1891.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] He then returned to the University of Michigan, where he was professor of geology and paleontology.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] His work in geology was not so significant as his teaching and popular lectures and writing in this field.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] He was much concerned with reconciling science and religion.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] He was an advocate of theistic evolution.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] The fish **Clear chub** *Hybopsis winchelli* (Girard, 1856) is named after him.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] The University of Michigan named a wing of the West Quad dormitory after Winchell, and Ann Arbor honored him with Winchell Park, a neighborhood park on the city's east side.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] Winchell's name was removed from the dormitory in 2018, and the park was renamed after former Ann Arbor Public Schools board president Harold J.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alexander-winchell] In removing Winchell's name, the university described his *Preadamites* as an "unambiguously racist" work.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] Lane was educated at Harvard University and received his A.B. degree in 1883.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] Between 1883 and 1885 he taught mathematics at Harvard, then studied at the University of Heidelberg until 1887 before returning to Harvard to earn his Ph.D. in 1888.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] The following year he joined the Michigan State Geologic Survey as a petrographer, and he remained in that post into 1892 while also serving as an instructor at the Michigan College of Mines.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] He became assistant state geologist for Michigan in 1892, and from 1899 to 1909 he was the state geologist.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] Finally, he joined Tufts College in 1892, becoming the Pearson professor of geology and mineralogy.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] He retired from the college in 1936 as professor emeritus.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] While at Tufts, he served as vice president of the AAAS Division of Geology in 1907.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] He received an honorary D.Sc. from Tufts in 1913.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] From 1922 and 1946 he was chairman for the Committee on the Measurement of Geologic Time for the National Research Council.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] He served as a member of the Board of Visitors at Harvard Observatory in 1924.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] Alfred Lane was appointed as consultant of science to the Library of Congress in 1929; the first person to hold that post.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] In 1931, he was president of the Geological Society of America.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] He was awarded the Ballou Medal by Tufts College in 1940 for "distinguished service to education and the nation".
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/alfred-church-lane] During his career, he authored 1,087 publications.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] Lawson was born on July 25, 1861, in Anstruther, Scotland.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] He moved to Hamilton, Ontario, Canada with his parents at age six.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] In 1883, he received his B.A. degree in natural science from the University of Toronto.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] He worked for the Geological Survey of Canada while pursuing his graduate degrees.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] He received his M.A. from the University of Toronto in 1885, and his Ph.D. from Johns Hopkins University in 1888.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] In 1890, he left the Geological Survey of Canada to work as a consulting geologist in Vancouver.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] In October of the same year, he accepted a position as assistant professor of Mineralogy and Geology at the University of California in Berkeley.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] He became a full professor in 1892, and a professor emeritus from 1928 to his death on June 16, 1952.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] Lawson was elected to the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1915, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1924, and the American Philosophical Society in 1925.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] He was president of the Geological Society of America in 1926.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] He was a consulting geologist for the construction of the Golden Gate Bridge in the 1930s.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] His home in the La Loma Park area of the Berkeley Hills in Berkeley, California, called the "Andrew Cowper Lawson House" (1908), was especially designed for him by noted architect Bernard Maybeck to withstand earthquakes.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] The house is an official city designated Berkeley Landmark.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] The mineral Lawsonite is named for him, as is the Lawson Adit, originally a mining construction research tunnel on UC Berkeley's campus.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] 13,165 feet) in Sequoia National Park was officially named after him in 1976.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/andrew-lawson] 1,128 feet), located west of the Briones Hills in Contra Costa County, California, is named for him.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] Between 1951 and 1953, he was a pilot in the Royal Air Force.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] In 1957, he obtained a degree in geology from the University of Cambridge.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] Later that year he moved to Canada, where he worked in Sudbury as a geologist for Falconbridge Nickel Mines.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] In 1959 he moved to Kingston, Ontario to attend Queen's University.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] He received an MSc (1961) and a PhD degree (1964) for his research on nickel deposits.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] Naldrett took a position working in the Geophysical Laboratory of the Carnegie Institution of Washington.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] In 1967, he returned to Canada as an assistant professor at the University of Toronto.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] In 1972, he was appointed a full Professor, and University Professor in 1984.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] He worked there until his retirement in 1998.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] The university made him an Emeritus Professor.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] Naldrett authored or co-authored 254 refereed publications, plus wrote or edited eight books covering his research in geology, mineralogy and chemistry of magmatic sulfide deposits and related rocks.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/anthony-j-naldrett] In addition to his research, he consulted for over 35 companies including Chevron Corporation, Falconbridge, Western Mining Corporation, BHP, Rio Tinto, Cominco-American, Voisey's Bay Nickel, and Kennecott.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] Hague was born December 3, 1840, in Boston, Massachusetts, to William Hague, a clergyman.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] He graduated from Sheffield Scientific School at Yale University in 1863.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] He then spent three years in Germany, studying at the universities of Göttingen and Heidelberg, and at the Freiberg Mining Academy.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] In 1867 he returned to the United States, and was appointed assistant geologist on the U.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] S. geological exploration of the 40th parallel under Clarence King.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] In Volume II—“Descriptive Geology”—of the report of the exploration, which was the joint work of Hague and Samuel F.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] Emmons, there is given the results of a detailed geological survey across the Cordilleras of North America, from the Great Plains to the Sierra Nevada range in California.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] This work included a geological atlas of maps and sections, which was completed after a great deal of hardship, the map of the Great Basin being accomplished before the completion of either the Union or Central Pacific Railroad.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] On the termination of this work in 1877, he received the appointment of government geologist of Guatemala, and traveled extensively over the republic, visiting the principal mining regions and the canters of volcanic activity.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] In 1878 he was engaged by the Chinese government to examine gold, silver, and lead mines in northern China.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] Geological Survey in 1879, he returned to the United States, and became one of its geologists.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] He was sent to Nevada, and made a report on the “Geology of the Eureka District.” In 1883 he was made geologist of the Yellowstone Park division, and assigned to the study of the geysers of that district in connection with the extinct volcanic regions of the Rocky Mountains.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] He was a member of scientific societies both in the United States and Europe and in 1885 was elected to the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] He received an Sc.D. degree from Columbia University in 1901, and an LL.D. degree from Aberdeen University.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] In 1903, he was elected to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] He was a member of the commission appointed by the National Academy of Sciences at the request of the United States Government in 1896 to prepare plans for the National Forest preserves.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] He was vice president of the International Congresses of Geologists held in Paris in 1900, in Stockholm in 1910 and in Toronto in 1913.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] He became president of the Geological Society of America in 1910.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/arnold-hague] Hague died May 14, 1917, in Washington, D.C.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/b-clark-burchfiel] Burchfiel joined the MIT faculty in 1976.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/b-clark-burchfiel] Over his career he wrote close to 200 papers and mentored more than 50 graduate students.
[src:b-clark-burchfiel/b-clark-burchfiel] Burchfiel died on February 9, 2024, at the age of 89.
